Mot: The only way to maximise my profit is by contributing all I have, even if the others do not do so. That is, if I gave all of my money (EUR4), while the others kept theirs, my contribution (EUR4) will double, so the total money my GROUP has is 4*2 + 4 + 4 = 16. And since the money is divided among all participants evenly, each of us will get more than 4 euro (16/3 > 12/3)
PARH2: The study was trying to show that people who value community and who have a "collectivistic" (as Hofstede would call it) view on society or who come from a collectivistic society are more inclined to help others (financially too) than those who are more individualistic. / The study aims to investigate whether having a strong "sense of community" encourages people to share. I also think that logic is also important: if you calculate how much you get by sharing, you realise that you cannot lose anything if you do share. Also, you lose an opportunity to gain more if you do NOT share.

Mot: Because I was a bit late and had to park my car at the university parking lot, I planned that I could pay for the parking time of maximum 1 hour with 1 euro (as the study takes 30 minutes and walking to and back from the parking garage takes time, I decided to be sure and take 1 euro for the parking as 100 percent sure, so that I don't need to pay for parking the car to just participate in this study). Therefore, I thought I'd risk the remaining 3 euro to try and maximize the payback. If I won't get more than 1 euro, that's fine, because I do not have to pay for the parking of my car for this 30-60 minutes, and I don't consider the lost potential of a few euro a big loss, which means that if I get more than 4 euro at the end, I am happy, and if not, it's also fine. I have to say that if I hadn't been so late, I would have gambled the whole 4 euro to be able to see what the payback is, but now that there are some costs related to being here (indirectly through parking my car), I decided not to do that. I would also like to add that the previous question of what amount of contributing to the group product will give you the highest payback. That all depends on what the other group members also contribute, so the question was unclear: did you mean that if others contribute nothing? Or if others contribute the whole amount? Or if everyone contributes the same amount as you? I didn't understand your question, as it depends on the situation, and the situation was not stated clearly.
PARH2: I think the study tried to examine how people make decisions: what things they take into account while weighing the different possibilities of action they can take in the situation. Whether people have values and beliefs, such as trust in strangers, and how safe they feel in general, and how personally responsible or 'fatalistic' they are of their lives - these values and beliefs are probably somehow related to decision making, and I believe this is what this experiment was about: to examine the relations of different values and how much someone contributes to the group from which they know nothing of. What is the participant's belief in general "good" in the world, and how much does this affect the decision making of this person?

Mot: Dit onderzoek is gebaseerd op het prisoner's dilemma. Er zijn twee gevangenen die kunnen kiezen om elkaar te verraden of te zwijgen. Als ze allebei zwijgen krijgen ze twee jaar, als ze elkaar verraden krijgen ze beiden vier jaar en als een de ander verraadt terwijl de ander zwijgt dan gaat de verrader vrijuit en krijgt de zwijger 8 jaar. Voor de persoon zou het verraden en verzwegen worden het meest profitabel zijn, maar dat weet de ander ook, dus zal deze ook verraden. Het is dus het allerveiligst om beide partijen te laten zwijgen, zo zal niemand verraden worden. In dit onderzoek is het het meest profitabel voor de persoon als ze niks inleggen en de ander wel en het meest profitabel voor de groep als iedereen evenveel inlegt, namelijk alles. Mensen zullen zelf ook voor zichzelf kiezen en besluiten minder bij te dragen omdat je er niet op kan vertrouwen dat iedereen evenveel bijdraagt, dus is het het veiligst voor de persoon om ook zelf minder bij te dragen. Zo verlies je niet al te veel geld, maar als de rest alsnog besluit veel bij te dragen verdien je zelf meer geld. In beide gevallen speel je relatief veilig. Dit is dan ook de redenering achter mijn gedachtegang.
PARH2: Zoals eerder genoemde uitleg van het prisoner's dilemma; het wilt laten zien dat het het meest profitabel is om mee te werken met de groep en al je vertrouwen in de groep te gooien, maar dat je eigenlijk niet op anderen kunt vertrouwen; ze zullen altijd eerst naar hun eigenbelang kijken.
